# Essential Git Commands for Beginners

These commands are used to initialize a project and push your code to GitHub for the first time.

| Command | Description |
| :--- | :--- |
| **`git init`** | Initializes a new local Git repository in your current folder. |
| **`git status`** | Shows the current state of your repository (tracked, untracked, and modified files). |
| **`git add <file_name>`** | Stages a specific file, preparing it to be committed. |
| **`git add .`** | Stages all files and changes in the current directory at once. |
| **`git commit -m "Message"`** | Saves a permanent snapshot (version) of the staged files with a descriptive message. |
| **`git branch -M main`** | Renames the default branch to `main`. |
| **`git remote add origin <URL>`** | Links your local repository to a remote repository on GitHub using its URL. |
| **`git push -u origin main`** | Uploads your local commits to the remote GitHub repository for the first time. |
| **`git clone <URL>`** | Downloads an existing project or tool from GitHub to your local machine. |
